article.headline: Swoopes, Thompson combine for 41 points
article.linkText: Comets extend Mystics' losing streak to nine
article.story:
HOUSTON (AP) -- When Sheryl Swoopes and Tina Thompson are playing
well at the same time, the Houston Comets are hard to beat.

Swoopes scored 23 points and Thompson added 18 as the Comets
beat Washington 76-54 on Saturday night for their third straight
win.

"It felt good to come out and play the way we did and put that
kind of game together for most of the 40 minutes we were out
there," Swoopes said. "Overall, I thought we played an incredible
game, and this is definitely the kind of game we were waiting to
have."

The Comets (9-7) have won four of five at the end of a six-game
homestand.

Washington (2-12) has lost nine straight since a 79-72 victory
over San Antonio on June 10. The Mystics have not won on the road
since opening night.

Chamique Holdsclaw led the Mystics with 18 points and nine
rebounds.

Washington fell to 1-9 against the Comets. The Mystics have
never won in Houston.

"It's frustrating for me," Holdsclaw said. "We're trying to
find our niche right now as a team, but we are just struggling.
We're not playing good defense at times, and we're not executing."

The Comets had a 19-point lead at halftime as Swoopes and
Thompson combined for 29 first-half points, outscoring Washington
by two.

The Comets led by as many as 32 points in the second half.

"Houston did tonight what a championship team does,"
Washington head coach Marianne Stanley said. "They take advantage
of your vulnerability. It's not just one thing with us, but we
didn't shoot the ball particularly well.

Houston assistant coach Alisa Scott received medical attention
on the baseline after fainting with just over seven minutes left in
the game. Scott passed out near the Houston bench after suffering
from light-headedness and dehydration. She was helped to her feet
and taken to the locker room by Comets trainer Michelle Leget.
